# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 What is Server-Side Development?

**Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Standard):**
> **Server-Side Development** refers to the branch of web programming where the *business logic, data processing, database interaction, and dynamic content generation* are executed on a **remote web server** (e.g., Apache, Nginx, IIS) rather than on the user's browser. The client (browser) only receives the final rendered output (usually HTML/CSS/JS) via protocols such as **HTTP/HTTPS**.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Board Definition to memorize verbatim:**
> "Server-side scripting produces output that is *not* dependent on the client's environment, OS, or browser version. Code runs on the server, and only the result is sent to the client over the network."

### Conceptual Analogy — The Restaurant Kitchen 🍳

Imagine a restaurant:
- **You (the customer)** sit at the table holding the **menu**. You are the **client (browser)**.
- **The waiter** takes your order and walks to the kitchen. He is the **HTTP request**.
- **The kitchen** has stoves, ingredients, recipes, and a chef. This is the **web server** running **server-side code (PHP)**.
- The chef prepares the dish based on the order (the PHP code runs, fetches data from the database, builds HTML).
- The waiter returns with the **finished plate** to your table — the browser **never sees the recipe** or the raw ingredients. It only sees the final **HTML page**.

This is exactly how server-side development works: the **logic is hidden**, **secure**, and **centralized** on the server.

### Server-Side vs Client-Side at a Glance

| Aspect | Client-Side | Server-Side |
|---|---|---|
| **Runs on** | User's Browser (Chrome, Firefox) | Web Server (Apache, Nginx) |
| **Languages** | HTML, CSS, **JavaScript** | **PHP**, Python, Java, Node.js, Ruby |
| **Source Visibility** | Visible (View Source) | Hidden — secure |
| **Database Access** | ❌ Not possible directly | ✅ Native (MySQL, PostgreSQL) |
| **Performance** | Depends on client hardware | Depends on server capacity |
| **Examples** | Form validation, animations | Login auth, payments, APIs |

> [!NOTE]
> PHP stands for **"PHP: Hypertext Preprocessor"** (originally **Personal Home Page**, created by **Rasmus Lerdorf in 1994**). It is an **open-source**, **server-side**, **HTML-embedded scripting language** widely used for dynamic web content.

### Why PHP for KTU?

According to the **KTU 2024 Scheme PECST742 syllabus**, PHP is the primary pedagogical vehicle for teaching server-side concepts because it is:
- **Loosely typed** (no strict variable declarations needed).
- **Embedded directly into HTML** (mixing `<?php ... ?>` with HTML is natural).
- **Cross-platform** (Windows/Linux/macOS).
- **Database-friendly** (native **MySQLi/PDO** extensions).
- **Industry-veteran** — powers **WordPress, Facebook (early), Wikipedia, Magento**.

---

## 1.2 Quick Tour of PHP

### PHP Tagging — How PHP is Embedded in HTML

PHP code is enclosed in special tags. When the server encounters these tags, it hands control to the **PHP interpreter**:

```php
<?php
    // PHP code lives here
    echo "Hello, KTU!";
?>
```

The four valid PHP tag styles (memorize all for KTU viva):

| Tag Style | Form | Status |
|---|---|---|
| **Canonical** | `<?php ... ?>` | ✅ Always recommended |
| **Short Echo** | `<?= $variable ?>` | ✅ Equivalent to `<?php echo $variable; ?>` |
| **Short** | `<? ... ?>` | ⚠️ Requires `short_open_tag` in `php.ini` |
| **Script** | `<script language="php">` | ❌ Removed in PHP 7+ |

### Comments in PHP

```php
<?php
    // Single-line comment — C++ style
    # Single-line comment — Shell style
    /*
       Multi-line comment
       Spans multiple lines — C style
    */
?>
```

### Variables in PHP

**Definition:** A variable is a named memory location that stores a value. In PHP, **all variables begin with a `$` sign** and are **dynamically typed** (no type declaration needed).

```php
<?php
    $name     = "Anu";          // String
    $rollNo   = 45;              // Integer
    $cgpa     = 8.76;            // Float
    $isKtu    = true;            // Boolean
    $subjects = array("CS", "Math"); // Array
    $nothing  = NULL;            // NULL
?>
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Pitfall:** PHP variable names are **case-sensitive** (`$Name` ≠ `$name`). Class names and function names are **case-insensitive** (`echo` and `ECHO` are identical).

### PHP Data Types — 8 Primitive Types

1. **Scalar (4):** `int`, `float` (double), `string`, `bool`
2. **Compound (2):** `array`, `object`
3. **Special (2):** `resource`, `NULL`

### Output Statements

```php
<?php
    echo "Hello";     // Language construct — faster, no return value
    print("World");   // Language construct — returns 1
    print_r($arr);    // Prints arrays/objects in human-readable form
    var_dump($var);   // Prints type + value — best for debugging
?>
```

---

## 1.3 Object-Oriented Design — The Big Picture

**Definition (KTU Board Standard):**
> **Object-Oriented Design (OOD)** is a software design methodology that models a system as a collection of interacting **objects**, each bundling **data (attributes)** and **behavior (methods)**, derived from **classes** (blueprints). OOD is built upon four foundational pillars: **Encapsulation, Abstraction, Inheritance, and Polymorphism**.

### Real-World Analogy — The Car Blueprint 🚗

A **Class** is a *blueprint* (the engineering drawing of a car).
An **Object** is a *real car* built from that blueprint.
- **Attributes** (data): color, model, engineCC, currentSpeed
- **Methods** (behavior): start(), accelerate(), brake(), refuel()

You can build **many cars** (objects) from **one blueprint** (class) — this is **object instantiation**.

> [!NOTE]
> The **four pillars of OOP** (memorize for KTU 2-mark questions):
> 1. **Encapsulation** — bundling data + methods, hiding internals.
> 2. **Abstraction** — showing only essentials, hiding complexity.
> 3. **Inheritance** — child class acquiring parent class properties.
> 4. **Polymorphism** — same interface, different implementations.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Program Control in PHP

PHP supports the standard imperative control structures. They are **byte-for-byte identical** to C/Java syntax — a deliberate KTU-friendly design choice.

### 2.1.1 Conditional Statements

#### `if` Statement
```php
<?php
    $marks = 78;
    if ($marks >= 50) {
        echo "Pass";
    }
?>
```

#### `if...else`
```php
<?php
    if ($marks >= 50) {
        echo "Pass";
    } else {
        echo "Fail";
    }
?>
```

#### `if...elseif...else` (Note: `else if` and `elseif` are equivalent in PHP)
```php
<?php
    if ($marks >= 90)      echo "A+";
    elseif ($marks >= 80)  echo "A";
    elseif ($marks >= 70)  echo "B+";
    elseif ($marks >= 60)  echo "B";
    elseif ($marks >= 50)  echo "C";
    else                   echo "F";
?>
```

#### `switch` — Multi-way Branching
```php
<?php
    $day = 3;
    switch ($day) {
        case 1: echo "Monday";  break;
        case 2: echo "Tuesday"; break;
        case 3: echo "Wednesday"; break;
        default: echo "Other day";
    }
?>
```

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Trap:** Forgetting `break;` in a `switch` causes **fall-through** — execution continues into the next case. Always include `break;` unless fall-through is intentional.

#### Ternary Operator
```php
<?php
    $status = ($marks >= 50) ? "Pass" : "Fail";
    // PHP 7+ Null Coalescing
    $name = $username ?? "Guest";  // assigns "Guest" if $username is NULL
?>
```

### 2.1.2 Looping Constructs

| Loop Type | When to Use | Syntax |
|---|---|---|
| `while` | Pre-condition, may not execute at all | `while (cond) { ... }` |
| `do...while` | Post-condition, executes **at least once** | `do { ... } while (cond);` |
| `for` | Known iteration count | `for (init; cond; update) { ... }` |
| `foreach` | Iterating over arrays | `foreach ($arr as $val) { ... }` |

#### `while` Loop
```php
<?php
    $i = 1;
    while ($i <= 5) {
        echo "$i ";
        $i++;
    }
?>
```

#### `for` Loop
```php
<?php
    for ($i = 1; $i <= 5; $i++) {
        echo "$i ";
    }
?>
```

#### `foreach` Loop — **The PHP Superpower** for arrays
```php
<?php
    $fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Cherry"];
    foreach ($fruits as $fruit) {
        echo "$fruit ";
    }
    // Output: Apple Banana Cherry
?>
```

#### `foreach` with Key-Value Pairs
```php
<?php
    $ages = ["Anu" => 20, "Rahul" => 22];
    foreach ($ages as $name => $age) {
        echo "$name is $age years old.<br>";
    }
?>
```

### 2.1.3 Jump Statements

| Statement | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `break` | Exit the current loop or switch immediately |
| `continue` | Skip the rest of current iteration, go to next |
| `exit;` / `die();` | Terminate the entire script |

---

## 2.2 Functions in PHP

**Definition (KTU Standard):**
> A **function** is a named, reusable block of statements that performs a specific task. PHP has **>1000 built-in functions** plus the ability to define **user-defined functions**.

### 2.2.1 User-Defined Functions

```php
<?php
    function functionName($param1, $param2 = "default") {
        // body
        return $result;
    }
?>
```

**Example — Area of a Circle:**
```php
<?php
    function circleArea($radius) {
        return pi() * $radius * $radius;
    }
    echo circleArea(5);  // 78.5398...
?>
```

### 2.2.2 Variable Scope in PHP

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 High-Yield Topic:** Understand all 6 scopes:

| Scope | Visibility | Lifetime |
|---|---|---|
| **Local** | Inside a function | Until function returns |
| **Global** | Outside all functions | Until script ends (accessible via `global` keyword or `$GLOBALS[]`) |
| **Static** | Inside a function, retains value between calls | Until script ends |
| **Function Parameter** | Inside function only | Until function returns |
| **Superglobals** | Anywhere (`$_GET`, `$_POST`, `$_SESSION`, `$_SERVER`, `$_COOKIE`, `$_FILES`, `$_REQUEST`, `$_ENV`, `$GLOBALS`) | Always available |
| **Class member** | Via object/class context | Lifetime of object |

#### Demonstrating Scope Rules

```php
<?php
    $x = 10;  // GLOBAL

    function test() {
        $y = 20;                 // LOCAL
        global $x;                // Import global into function
        echo $x + $y;             // 30
    }

    function counter() {
        static $count = 0;        // STATIC — persists across calls
        $count++;
        echo $count . " ";
    }
    counter(); counter(); counter();  // Output: 1 2 3
?>
```

### 2.2.3 Variable-Length Argument Lists (PHP 5.6+)

```php
<?php
    function sum(...$numbers) {
        return array_sum($numbers);
    }
    echo sum(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);  // 15
?>
```

### 2.2.4 Anonymous Functions and Closures

```php
<?php
    $greet = function($name) {
        return "Hello, $name!";
    };
    echo $greet("Anu");  // Hello, Anu!
?>
```

### 2.2.5 Arrow Functions (PHP 7.4+)

```php
<?php
    $square = fn($n) => $n * $n;
    echo $square(5);  // 25
?>
```

---

## 2.3 Arrays in PHP

**Definition (KTU Board Standard):**
> An **array** in PHP is an **ordered map** (key-value pairs) that can hold multiple values under a single variable name. PHP arrays are exceptionally flexible — keys can be **integers OR strings**, and values can be **any type** (mixed-type allowed). PHP does not have separate ArrayList/HashMap classes — **one unified structure** handles both.

### 2.3.1 Three Types of Arrays

#### 1. Indexed Arrays (Numeric Keys, Auto-Assigned)
```php
<?php
    $fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Cherry"];  // PHP 5.4+ short syntax
    // Equivalent older syntax: $fruits = array("Apple", "Banana", "Cherry");
    echo $fruits[0];  // Apple
    echo $fruits[2];  // Cherry
?>
```

#### 2. Associative Arrays (String Keys — like a HashMap)
```php
<?php
    $student = [
        "name"  => "Anu",
        "roll"  => 45,
        "cgpa"  => 8.76,
        "dept"  => "CSE"
    ];
    echo $student["name"];  // Anu
?>
```

#### 3. Multidimensional Arrays (Arrays of Arrays)
```php
<?php
    $marks = [
        "Anu"   => ["Math" => 90, "CS" => 95],
        "Rahul" => ["Math" => 78, "CS" => 82]
    ];
    echo $marks["Anu"]["CS"];  // 95
?>
```

### 2.3.2 Essential Array Functions (KTU High-Yield)

| Function | Purpose | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `count($arr)` / `sizeof($arr)` | Number of elements | `count($fruits)` → 3 |
| `array_push($arr, $val)` | Append to end | `array_push($fruits, "Date")` |
| `array_pop($arr)` | Remove from end | `$last = array_pop($fruits);` |
| `array_shift($arr)` | Remove from front | `$first = array_shift($fruits);` |
| `array_unshift($arr, $val)` | Add to front | `array_unshift($fruits, "Mango");` |
| `in_array($val, $arr)` | Check existence | `in_array("Apple", $fruits)` → true |
| `array_search($val, $arr)` | Find key of value | `array_search("Banana", $fruits)` → 1 |
| `array_merge($a, $b)` | Merge arrays | `array_merge($a, $b)` |
| `array_keys($arr)` | Extract all keys | `array_keys($student)` |
| `array_values($arr)` | Extract all values | `array_values($student)` |
| `sort($arr)` | Sort ascending by value | re-indexes numerically |
| `rsort($arr)` | Sort descending by value | re-indexes numerically |
| `asort($arr)` | Sort asc, preserve keys | for associative |
| `ksort($arr)` | Sort by keys ascending | for associative |
| `array_map(fn, $arr)` | Apply fn to each | `array_map('strtoupper', $arr)` |
| `array_filter($arr, fn)` | Filter by predicate | keeps only true values |
| `array_reduce($arr, fn, $init)` | Reduce to single | accumulator pattern |
| `explode($delim, $str)` | String → Array | `explode(",", "a,b,c")` |
| `implode($delim, $arr)` | Array → String | `implode("-", [1,2,3])` → "1-2-3" |

---

## 2.4 Classes and Objects in PHP

### 2.4.1 Defining a Class

```php
<?php
    class Student {
        // Properties (attributes)
        public $name;
        public $rollNo;
        private $cgpa;       // Encapsulation: hidden from outside

        // Constant
        const UNIVERSITY = "KTU";

        // Constructor — called on object creation
        public function __construct($name, $rollNo, $cgpa) {
            $this->name   = $name;
            $this->rollNo = $rollNo;
            $this->cgpa   = $cgpa;
            echo "Object created for $name<br>";
        }

        // Destructor — called when object is destroyed
        public function __destruct() {
            echo "Object destroyed for $this->name<br>";
        }

        // Method
        public function display() {
            echo "Name: $this->name, Roll: $this->rollNo, CGPA: $this->cgpa<br>";
        }

        // Getter (encapsulation helper)
        public function getCgpa() {
            return $this->cgpa;
        }

        // Setter with validation
        public function setCgpa($cgpa) {
            if ($cgpa >= 0 && $cgpa <= 10) {
                $this->cgpa = $cgpa;
            }
        }
    }

    // Creating objects
    $s1 = new Student("Anu", 45, 8.76);
    $s2 = new Student("Rahul", 46, 9.12);
    $s1->display();
    echo "University: " . Student::UNIVERSITY . "<br>";  // Scope Resolution
?>
```

### 2.4.2 The Four Pillars — Implemented in PHP

#### Pillar 1: **Encapsulation** (via access modifiers)

| Modifier | Same Class | Subclass | Outside |
|---|---|---|---|
| `public` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |
| `protected` | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ |
| `private` | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ |

#### Pillar 2: **Abstraction** (via `abstract` classes or `interface`)

```php
<?php
    // Abstract class — cannot be instantiated, only inherited
    abstract class Shape {
        abstract public function area();
        public function describe() {
            echo "I am a shape with area " . $this->area();
        }
    }

    class Circle extends Shape {
        private $r;
        public function __construct($r) { $this->r = $r; }
        public function area() { return pi() * $this->r * $this->r; }
    }

    // Interface — pure contract (all methods abstract)
    interface Drawable {
        public function draw();
    }
?>
```

#### Pillar 3: **Inheritance**

```php
<?php
    class Animal {
        public $name;
        public function speak() { echo "...\n"; }
    }

    class Dog extends Animal {
        public function speak() {                  // Method overriding
            echo "$this->name says Woof!\n";
        }
        public function fetch() {                   // New method
            echo "$this->name fetches the ball.\n";
        }
    }

    $d = new Dog();
    $d->name = "Bruno";
    $d->speak();   // Bruno says Woof!
    $d->fetch();   // Bruno fetches the ball.
?>
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Rule:** PHP supports **single inheritance** for classes (`extends` only one parent), but **multiple inheritance of interfaces** is allowed (`implements A, B, C`).

#### Pillar 4: **Polymorphism**

```php
<?php
    interface Payment {
        public function pay($amount);
    }
    class CreditCard implements Payment {
        public function pay($amount) { echo "Paid ₹$amount via Card"; }
    }
    class UPI implements Payment {
        public function pay($amount) { echo "Paid ₹$amount via UPI"; }
    }
    class Cash implements Payment {
        public function pay($amount) { echo "Paid ₹$amount in Cash"; }
    }

    function checkout(Payment $method, $amt) {
        $method->pay($amt);  // Same call, different behavior
    }
?>
```

---

## 2.5 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Syntax | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| **PHP tag** | `<?php ... ?>` | Only canonical form is portable |
| **Variable** | `$name` | Case-sensitive, `$` prefix mandatory |
| **Constant** | `const NAME = value;` or `define("NAME", val);` | Cannot be reassigned |
| **Concatenation** | `.` (period) | `echo "Hi " . $name;` |
| **Interpolation** | `"Hi $name"` (double-quote only) | Single-quote treats `$` as literal |
| **Ternary** | `$x = (cond) ? a : b;` | Returns value |
| **Null Coalescing** | `$x = $a ?? $b;` | PHP 7+ |
| **Spaceship** | `$x <=> $y;` | Returns -1, 0, or 1 (PHP 7+) |
| **Function def** | `function name($a, $b=1) { return $a+$b; }` | Default args allowed |
| **Static var** | `static $count = 0;` | Persists between calls |
| **Class def** | `class Name { ... }` | One per file conventionally |
| **Inheritance** | `class Child extends Parent` | Single only |
| **Interface** | `class C implements I1, I2` | All methods must be implemented |
| **Abstract** | `abstract class C { abstract function f(); }` | Cannot `new` abstract |
| **Access** | `public` / `protected` / `private` | Default: `var` = public |
| **`$this`** | Refers to current object | Inside class methods only |
| **`self::`** | Refers to current class (compile time) | Use for constants/static |
| **`static::`** | Late static binding (runtime) | Honors overriding in subclasses |
| **`parent::`** | Refers to parent class | `parent::__construct();` |
| **`instanceof`** | Type check operator | `$d instanceof Dog` |
