### **Question B (14 Marks)** — *Internal Choice Alternative*

> **[KTU University Exam – Model Paper 1, PECST742 Module 3]**

#### (a) (7 marks) — Explain the three types of arrays in PHP with examples. Write a program to sort an associative array of student names and marks in descending order by marks.

**Model Answer:**

**Three Array Types (3 marks):**

**1. Indexed Array (1 mark):**
Keys are numeric integers (auto-assigned starting at 0).
```php
<?php
    $colors = ["Red", "Green", "Blue"];
    echo $colors[0];  // Red
?>
```

**2. Associative Array (1 mark):**
Keys are user-defined strings — like a hashmap/dictionary.
```php
<?php
    $student = ["name"=>"Anu", "roll"=>45, "cgpa"=>8.76];
    echo $student["name"];  // Anu
?>
```

**3. Multidimensional Array (1 mark):**
Arrays nested inside arrays — used to represent tables/matrices.
```php
<?php
    $class = [
        "Anu"   => ["Math"=>90, "CS"=>95],
        "Rahul" => ["Math"=>78, "CS"=>82]
    ];
    echo $class["Anu"]["CS"];  // 95
?>
```

**Sort Program (4 marks):**

```php
<?php
    // Sample data
    $marks = [
        "Anu"    => 78,
        "Rahul"  => 92,
        "Sneha"  => 88,
        "Vivek"  => 95,
        "Meera"  => 81
    ];

    // arsort = sort by value DESCENDING, keep keys intact
    arsort($marks);

    echo "<h3>Ranking (Descending by Marks)</h3>";
    echo "<table border='1' cellpadding='5'>";
    echo "<tr><th>Rank</th><th>Name</th><th>Marks</th></tr>";

    $rank = 1;
    foreach ($marks as $name => $score) {
        echo "<tr><td>$rank</td><td>$name</td><td>$score</td></tr>";
        $rank++;
    }
    echo "</table>";

    // Topper extraction
    $topper = array_key_first($marks);   // PHP 7.3+
    echo "🏆 Topper: $topper with {$marks[$topper]} marks";
?>
```

**Why `arsort`?** Because it sorts by value in **descending order** while **preserving the string keys** (student names). `rsort` would lose the names and re-index as 0, 1, 2, ...

#### (b) (7 marks) — Explain the concept of variable scope in PHP. Write a PHP program demonstrating the use of `global`, `local`, and `static` scopes.

**Model Answer:**

**Concept (3 marks):**
The **scope** of a variable is the context in which it is defined and accessible. PHP has several scopes:

| Scope | Description |
|---|---|
| **Local** | Declared inside a function; accessible only within that function. |
| **Global** | Declared outside any function; accessible everywhere except inside functions (must use `global` keyword). |
| **Static** | Declared inside a function with `static` keyword; retains its value between function calls. |
| **Superglobals** | Pre-defined arrays (`$_GET`, `$_POST`, `$_SESSION`, etc.) accessible in any scope. |

**Program (4 marks):**

```php
<?php
    $siteName = "KTU B.Tech Portal";  // GLOBAL

    function visitCounter() {
        static $count = 0;            // STATIC — value persists
        $count++;
        echo "Visit #$count to this function<br>";
    }

    function showSite() {
        global $siteName;             // bring global into local scope
        $localVar = "I am local";     // LOCAL
        echo "Welcome to $siteName<br>";
        echo "$localVar<br>";
        // echo $count;             // ❌ Error — $count not in scope
    }

    // Driver
    showSite();           // Welcome to KTU B.Tech Portal / I am local
    visitCounter();       // Visit #1
    visitCounter();       // Visit #2
    visitCounter();       // Visit #3

    // $GLOBALS superglobal alternative
    function showAlt() {
        echo $GLOBALS["siteName"];    // works without 'global' keyword
    }
    showAlt();
?>
```

**Key Insight (embedded in code):** The `static` keyword is the **only way** to preserve a function's local state across multiple invocations — useful for counters, caches, and memoization.

