# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Databases in the Web Context — Formal Definition

A **Database** is a structured, persistent, and logically organized collection of related data, typically managed by a **Database Management System (DBMS)**, which provides mechanisms for storage, retrieval, update, integrity, and security of data. In the context of **web development**, a web database refers to a database that is accessed and manipulated through a web application using a client-server model, where the web browser (client) communicates with a web server, which in turn communicates with the database server.

The integration of databases with the web is a foundational pillar of modern dynamic web applications — it enables persistent storage, user authentication, content management, e-commerce transactions, and analytics.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition (Verbatim Essence):**
> A *Web Database* is a database application designed to be managed and accessed through a web browser, employing a **three-tier architecture** comprising the **Client Tier (Presentation Layer)**, the **Application Tier (Logic Layer)**, and the **Data Tier (Database Layer)**.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The Restaurant Model

Imagine a **restaurant** to intuitively grasp the three-tier architecture:

- **Client Tier (Customer/Diner)** = The customer who views the menu (HTML/CSS rendered by browser) and places an order.
- **Application Tier (Waiter + Kitchen)** = The waiter (PHP/Python/Node.js server script) takes the order, processes it, and communicates with the kitchen.
- **Data Tier (Pantry/Storage Room)** = The kitchen's storage room (MySQL/PostgreSQL database) where all ingredients (data) are stored and retrieved.

Just as the customer never enters the storage room directly, the web client never connects to the database directly — all interactions are mediated by the application tier. This is the **fundamental security and architectural principle** of web-database integration.

## 1.3 SQL (Structured Query Language) — The Universal Data Language

**SQL (Structured Query Language)** is the standard declarative programming language used to define, manipulate, retrieve, and control access to data held in a **Relational Database Management System (RDBMS)**. It is governed by the **ANSI/ISO SQL standard**, though most RDBMS products (MySQL, Oracle, PostgreSQL) extend it with proprietary features.

| SQL Sub-language | Full Form | Purpose | Example Command |
|---|---|---|---|
| **DDL** | Data Definition Language | Defines/alters database schema | `CREATE`, `ALTER`, `DROP`, `TRUNCATE` |
| **DML** | Data Manipulation Language | Manipulates data within tables | `SELECT`, `INSERT`, `UPDATE`, `DELETE` |
| **DCL** | Data Control Language | Controls access/permissions | `GRANT`, `REVOKE` |
| **TCL** | Transaction Control Language | Manages transactions | `COMMIT`, `ROLLBACK`, `SAVEPOINT` |

> [!NOTE]
> **DQL (Data Query Language)** is often treated as a separate category containing only the `SELECT` statement, though technically it is a subset of DML in the formal ANSI classification.

## 1.4 Database APIs — The Bridge Between Code and Data

A **Database API (Application Programming Interface)** is a set of pre-defined functions, classes, and protocols that allows a software application to communicate with a database system without needing to know the low-level implementation details. The API acts as a **translation and abstraction layer** between the application's programming language and the database's native protocol.

For PHP-MySQL interaction, the major APIs are:

- **MySQL Native Driver (mysqlnd)** — The low-level C-based driver, **mandatory** since PHP 5.4.
- **mysqli (MySQL Improved Extension)** — Procedural and Object-Oriented API. **Recommended for beginners.**
- **PDO (PHP Data Objects)** — Database-agnostic, supports **12+ drivers** (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQLite, Oracle, etc.). **Recommended for production code.**

> [!WARNING]
> The legacy `mysql_*` functions (e.g., `mysql_connect()`, `mysql_query()`) were **officially deprecated in PHP 5.5 and removed in PHP 7.0**. KTU examiners will penalize answers using them. Always use `mysqli_*` or `PDO`.

## 1.5 MySQL — The Workhorse RDBMS

**MySQL** is an open-source, relational database management system that uses **SQL** as its query language. It follows the **client-server model**, uses the **InnoDB storage engine** (since v5.5) supporting ACID transactions and foreign keys, and is the **"M" in the LAMP/LEMP stack** (Linux, Apache/Nginx, MySQL, PHP).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Key MySQL Terminology for KTU:**
> - **Database** = A container of tables.
> - **Table** = A collection of related records arranged in rows and columns.
> - **Row / Record / Tuple** = A single data entry.
> - **Column / Field / Attribute** = A named data item within a record.
> - **Primary Key** = A column (or columns) that uniquely identifies each row. Cannot be NULL.
> - **Foreign Key** = A column that references the primary key of another table, enforcing referential integrity.

