# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The Three-Tier Web-Database Architecture — Operational Breakdown

The three-tier architecture is the **industry standard** for web-database applications. Each tier has a distinct responsibility, communicating only with its immediate neighbor:

**Tier 1 — Presentation Layer (Client Tier)**
- **Role:** Provides the user interface.
- **Technologies:** HTML5, CSS3, JavaScript, React, Angular.
- **Communication:** Sends HTTP/HTTPS requests; receives HTML/JSON/XML responses.
- **Never** communicates directly with the database.

**Tier 2 — Application/Logic Layer (Middle Tier)**
- **Role:** Processes business logic, validates input, authenticates users, generates queries.
- **Technologies:** PHP, Python (Django/Flask), Node.js (Express), Java (Spring).
- **Communication:** Receives HTTP requests, talks to the database via SQL/API, returns responses.

**Tier 3 — Data Layer (Database Tier)**
- **Role:** Stores, retrieves, and manages data with ACID guarantees.
- **Technologies:** MySQL, PostgreSQL, MongoDB, Oracle.
- **Communication:** Receives SQL commands, returns result sets to the application tier.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why Three Tiers and Not Two?** The two-tier model (client directly connects to DB) suffers from: (1) security risks exposing the DB, (2) inability to scale, (3) tight coupling of UI and data logic, and (4) poor maintainability. The three-tier model solves all four.

## 2.2 SQL Command Categories — Deep Dive

### 2.2.1 Data Definition Language (DDL)

DDL commands operate on the **schema** (structure) of the database, not on the data itself.

```sql
CREATE DATABASE college_db;
USE college_db;
CREATE TABLE students (
    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
    email VARCHAR(100) UNIQUE,
    age INT CHECK (age >= 17),
    dept_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (dept_id) REFERENCES departments(dept_id)
);
ALTER TABLE students ADD COLUMN cgpa DECIMAL(4,2);
DROP TABLE students;
TRUNCATE TABLE students;   -- Keeps structure, removes all rows (faster than DELETE)
```

### 2.2.2 Data Manipulation Language (DML)

DML commands operate on the **data** within tables.

```sql
INSERT INTO students (name, email, age) VALUES ('Anu', 'anu@ktu.in', 20);
SELECT id, name FROM students WHERE age > 18 ORDER BY name ASC;
UPDATE students SET email = 'new@ktu.in' WHERE id = 5;
DELETE FROM students WHERE id = 10;
```

### 2.2.3 Advanced SELECT — The High-Value KTU Concepts

```sql
-- Aggregate functions (HIGH KTU YIELD)
SELECT COUNT(*) AS total, AVG(age) AS avg_age, MAX(cgpa) AS highest
FROM students WHERE dept_id = 3;

-- GROUP BY + HAVING (distinguishes WHERE vs HAVING)
SELECT dept_id, COUNT(*) AS num_students
FROM students
GROUP BY dept_id
HAVING COUNT(*) > 50;

-- Joins (EXTREMELY HIGH KTU YIELD)
SELECT s.name, d.dept_name
FROM students s
INNER JOIN departments d ON s.dept_id = d.dept_id
WHERE s.cgpa > 8.0;

-- Subquery
SELECT name FROM students
WHERE dept_id = (SELECT dept_id FROM departments WHERE dept_name = 'CSE');
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **WHERE vs HAVING — KTU Favourite Distinction:**
> - `WHERE` filters **rows BEFORE** grouping (cannot use aggregate functions).
> - `HAVING` filters **groups AFTER** `GROUP BY` (CAN use aggregate functions).

## 2.3 Database APIs in PHP — The Two Main Approaches

### 2.3.1 The `mysqli` Extension (MySQL Improved)

The `mysqli` extension supports both **procedural** and **object-oriented** styles, providing improved performance, prepared statements, and multi-query support compared to the deprecated `mysql_*` API.

### 2.3.2 The PDO (PHP Data Objects) Extension

PDO is a **database-agnostic abstraction layer** introduced in PHP 5.1. It uses a uniform interface to access any of the 12+ supported databases, with native prepared statement support using named or positional placeholders.

## 2.4 KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet — MySQL Data Types

| Category | Type | Storage | Use Case |
|---|---|---|---|
| Integer | `TINYINT`, `SMALLINT`, `INT`, `BIGINT` | 1/2/4/8 bytes | IDs, counts |
| Decimal | `DECIMAL(M,D)`, `FLOAT`, `DOUBLE` | Variable | Money (use `DECIMAL`!) |
| String | `CHAR(n)`, `VARCHAR(n)` | Fixed/Variable | Names, short text |
| Text | `TINYTEXT`, `TEXT`, `LONGTEXT` | 255B–4GB | Articles, descriptions |
| Date/Time | `DATE`, `TIME`, `DATETIME`, `TIMESTAMP` | 3/4/8 bytes | Birth dates, logs |
| Binary | `BLOB`, `MEDIUMBLOB` | Variable | Images, files |
| Boolean | `BOOLEAN` (alias of `TINYINT(1)`) | 1 byte | Flags, status |

## 2.5 Connection Lifecycle — The 5-Stage Standard

Regardless of whether `mysqli` or `PDO` is used, every database interaction in PHP follows the same logical 5-stage lifecycle:

1. **Connect** — Open a connection to the MySQL server using credentials.
2. **Prepare Query** — Build the SQL string, optionally with placeholders.
3. **Execute** — Send the query to the MySQL server.
4. **Fetch/Process** — Retrieve and process the result set.
5. **Close** — Free resources and close the connection.

## 2.6 Prepared Statements vs. Direct Queries — The Security Pillar

A **prepared statement** (also called a parameterized statement) is a precompiled SQL template in which user-supplied values are sent separately from the SQL structure. The database engine **never** parses the user input as SQL code.

**Without prepared statements (VULNERABLE to SQL Injection):**
```php
$sql = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = '$name'";
// If $name = "' OR '1'='1", the query becomes a tautology and returns ALL users.
```

**With prepared statements (SECURE):**
```php
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = ?");
$stmt->execute([$name]);
// The value of $name is always treated as data, never as SQL.
```

> [!WARNING]
> **SQL Injection** is **OWASP #1** web vulnerability category. KTU questions on "security in web databases" almost always expect prepared statements as the answer.

## 2.7 Real-World Engineering Utility

This knowledge is the **backbone of every dynamic website** in production: authentication systems (login), e-commerce platforms (product catalogs, carts, orders), social networks (user profiles, posts, likes), content management systems (WordPress, Drupal), banking and fintech (transactions, audit logs), and data analytics dashboards. The **LAMP stack (Linux, Apache, MySQL, PHP)** powers an estimated **40%+ of all live websites**, including historically major platforms like Facebook and WordPress.com.

