# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Database Connection — mysqli Procedural Style (Exhaustive Walkthrough)

Below is the **complete, line-by-line annotated** demonstration of the most fundamental PHP-MySQL operation — establishing a connection. Every character, parameter, and return value is explained.

```php
<?php
// ============================================================
// STAGE 1: DEFINE CONNECTION PARAMETERS
// ============================================================
$host   = "localhost";    // Server address. "localhost" for local dev;
                         // use IP or domain in production.
$user   = "root";        // MySQL username. NEVER use "root" in production.
$pass   = "";            // MySQL password. Empty for default XAMPP setup.
$dbname = "college_db";  // Target database name.

// ============================================================
// STAGE 2: ESTABLISH CONNECTION (mysqli Procedural)
// ============================================================
$conn = mysqli_connect($host, $user, $pass, $dbname);
// Returns: mysqli object on success, FALSE on failure.

// ============================================================
// STAGE 3: ERROR HANDLING
// ============================================================
if (!$conn) {
    die("Connection failed: " . mysqli_connect_error());
    // die() terminates script execution and prints the message.
    // mysqli_connect_error() returns the last connection error string.
}
echo "Connected successfully to $dbname";

// ============================================================
// STAGE 4: SET CHARACTER ENCODING (CRITICAL FOR UNICODE)
// ============================================================
mysqli_set_charset($conn, "utf8mb4");
// Prevents character corruption (e.g., Indian names, emojis).

// ============================================================
// STAGE 5: EXECUTE A QUERY
// ============================================================
$sql    = "SELECT id, name, email FROM students WHERE age > 18";
$result = mysqli_query($conn, $sql);
// Returns: mysqli_result object on SELECT success, TRUE on non-SELECT
// success, FALSE on error.

// ============================================================
// STAGE 6: FETCH DATA (Multiple Options)
// ============================================================

// Option A: Fetch a single row as an associative array
$row = mysqli_fetch_assoc($result);
echo $row['name'] . " - " . $row['email'];

// Option B: Loop through ALL rows
while ($row = mysqli_fetch_assoc($result)) {
    echo "<p>ID: " . $row['id'] . " | Name: " . $row['name'] . "</p>";
}

// Option C: Fetch all rows at once into a 2D array
$all_rows = mysqli_fetch_all($result, MYSQLI_ASSOC);

// Option D: Count number of rows
$num_rows = mysqli_num_rows($result);

// ============================================================
// STAGE 7: CLOSE CONNECTION (release resources)
// ============================================================
mysqli_free_result($result);   // Free result set memory.
mysqli_close($conn);           // Close the database connection.
?>
```

**Step-by-Step Logic:**

1. **Parameter Definition:** Credentials are stored in variables (in production, use environment variables or `config.php` files outside the web root for security).
2. **`mysqli_connect()`:** Opens a TCP connection to the MySQL server, typically on port **3306** (default). Returns a connection handle.
3. **Error Check:** Always verify the connection — MySQL servers can be down, credentials wrong, or the database may not exist.
4. **Charset Setting:** `utf8mb4` is the **modern standard**; the older `utf8` is only 3-byte and cannot store all Unicode characters.
5. **Query Execution:** The SQL string is sent to MySQL; the server parses, optimizes, and executes it.
6. **Result Retrieval:** The `mysqli_fetch_*` family reads rows one by one from the result set buffer.
7. **Resource Cleanup:** Failing to close connections causes **resource leaks** under high load.

## 3.2 Database Connection — PDO Style (Exhaustive Walkthrough)

```php
<?php
// ============================================================
// STAGE 1: CONNECTION USING PDO
// ============================================================
$dsn = "mysql:host=localhost;dbname=college_db;charset=utf8mb4";
// DSN = Data Source Name — describes the connection target.

$options = [
    PDO::ATTR_ERRMODE            => PDO::ERRMODE_EXCEPTION,
    PDO::ATTR_DEFAULT_FETCH_MODE => PDO::FETCH_ASSOC,
    PDO::ATTR_EMULATE_PREPARES   => false,
];

try {
    $pdo = new PDO($dsn, "root", "", $options);
    echo "Connected via PDO";
} catch (PDOException $e) {
    die("Connection failed: " . $e->getMessage());
}

// ============================================================
// STAGE 2: PREPARED STATEMENT (SECURE QUERY)
// ============================================================
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("SELECT * FROM students WHERE dept_id = :dept AND age > :age");
$stmt->execute([':dept' => 3, ':age' => 18]);

// ============================================================
// STAGE 3: FETCH RESULTS
// ============================================================
$rows = $stmt->fetchAll();      // Fetch all as associative array.
$row  = $stmt->fetch();         // Fetch one row at a time.
$count = $stmt->rowCount();     // Number of affected rows.

// ============================================================
// STAGE 4: INSERT / UPDATE / DELETE WITH PREPARED STATEMENTS
// ============================================================
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("INSERT INTO students (name, email, age) VALUES (?, ?, ?)");
$stmt->execute(['Anu', 'anu@ktu.in', 20]);

// ============================================================
// STAGE 5: CLOSE CONNECTION (PDO closes when $pdo is unset or script ends)
?>
```

## 3.3 Complete CRUD Application in PHP — Analytical Matrix

The four fundamental persistent operations on data are universally abbreviated as **CRUD**. Below is the analytical matrix mapping each to its SQL, mysqli, and PDO equivalents:

| Operation | SQL Command | HTTP Verb | mysqli Function | PDO Method |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **C**reate | `INSERT INTO ...` | `POST` | `mysqli_query()` with INSERT | `prepare()` + `execute()` |
| **R**ead | `SELECT ... FROM ...` | `GET` | `mysqli_query()` + `mysqli_fetch_*()` | `query()` or `prepare()` + `fetch()` |
| **U**pdate | `UPDATE ... SET ...` | `PUT`/`POST` | `mysqli_query()` with UPDATE | `prepare()` + `execute()` |
| **D**elete | `DELETE FROM ...` | `DELETE`/`GET` | `mysqli_query()` with DELETE | `prepare()` + `execute()` |

## 3.4 SQL JOIN Types — Derivation of Behaviour

| JOIN Type | Returns |
|---|---|
| `INNER JOIN` | Rows with matches in **both** tables |
| `LEFT JOIN` | All rows from left table + matching from right (NULL if no match) |
| `RIGHT JOIN` | All rows from right table + matching from left (NULL if no match) |
| `FULL OUTER JOIN` | All rows from both tables (NULLs where no match) — *not supported in MySQL; emulate with `UNION`* |
| `CROSS JOIN` | Cartesian product (every row of A × every row of B) |
| `SELF JOIN` | A table joined to itself (e.g., employee-manager hierarchy) |

**Mathematical Expression of JOIN Cardinality:**

$$
\mid A \bowtie_{A.key = B.fk} B \mid \;=\; \sum_{a \in A} \mid \{ b \in B \; : \; b.fk = a.key \} \mid
$$

> [!NOTE]
> In plain English: the number of rows in an INNER JOIN equals the sum, for each row in A, of how many matching rows exist in B. For 1:N relationships, this simply gives `|A| × (avg matches per A)`.

## 3.5 Worked-Out Example — Full Signup-Login Flow (Analytical Trace)

**Scenario:** A user submits a registration form. The PHP script must insert the user, then later verify login credentials.

**Step 1 — Form Submission (HTML):**
```html
<form action="register.php" method="POST">
    <input name="username" type="text" required>
    <input name="password" type="password" required>
    <button type="submit">Register</button>
</form>
```

**Step 2 — Secure Password Storage (Hashing):**
```php
$username = $_POST['username'];
$password = $_POST['password'];

// NEVER store plaintext passwords!
$hash = password_hash($password, PASSWORD_BCRYPT);
// $hash is a 60-character string like "$2y$10$..." safe to store.
```

**Step 3 — Insert with Prepared Statement:**
```php
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("INSERT INTO users (username, password_hash) VALUES (?, ?)");
$stmt->execute([$username, $hash]);
```

**Step 4 — Login Verification:**
```php
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("SELECT password_hash FROM users WHERE username = ?");
$stmt->execute([$username]);
$row = $stmt->fetch();

if ($row && password_verify($password, $row['password_hash'])) {
    $_SESSION['user'] = $username;  // Start authenticated session.
    header("Location: dashboard.php");
} else {
    echo "Invalid credentials";
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Analytical Trace Summary:**
> 1. The browser sends `POST` to `register.php`.
> 2. PHP receives data, hashes the password with **bcrypt** (a one-way salted hash).
> 3. The username and hash are inserted via a **prepared statement** (immune to SQL injection).
> 4. On login, the hash is **re-verified** using `password_verify()` — bcrypt comparison is constant-time to prevent timing attacks.
> 5. On success, a PHP session is created; the user is redirected to the dashboard.

