### QUESTION B (14 Marks): SQL Operations and Database APIs

#### (a) Explain the different categories of SQL commands with examples for each. [7 Marks] [KTU University Exam - May 2023]

**Model Solution:**

SQL commands are broadly classified into **four categories** based on their function:

**(1) Data Definition Language (DDL):**
DDL commands define or alter the **structure** of database objects (tables, databases, indexes). These commands are auto-committed — changes cannot be rolled back.

| Command | Purpose | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `CREATE` | Create a new object | `CREATE TABLE books (id INT PRIMARY KEY, title VARCHAR(100));` |
| `ALTER`  | Modify structure | `ALTER TABLE books ADD COLUMN price DECIMAL(8,2);` |
| `DROP`   | Delete object permanently | `DROP TABLE books;` |
| `TRUNCATE` | Remove all rows, keep structure | `TRUNCATE TABLE books;` |

**(2) Data Manipulation Language (DML):**
DML commands manipulate the **data** within tables. These are transactional and can be rolled back.

| Command | Purpose | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `SELECT` | Retrieve data | `SELECT title, price FROM books WHERE price < 500;` |
| `INSERT` | Add new rows | `INSERT INTO books (title, price) VALUES ('PHP Guide', 450);` |
| `UPDATE` | Modify existing rows | `UPDATE books SET price = 400 WHERE id = 3;` |
| `DELETE` | Remove rows | `DELETE FROM books WHERE id = 5;` |

**(3) Data Control Language (DCL):**
DCL commands control **access permissions** to database objects.

```sql
GRANT SELECT, INSERT ON college_db.students TO 'appuser'@'localhost';
REVOKE INSERT ON college_db.students FROM 'appuser'@'localhost';
```

**(4) Transaction Control Language (TCL):**
TCL commands manage **transactions** to ensure ACID properties.

```sql
START TRANSACTION;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 1000 WHERE id = 1;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 1000 WHERE id = 2;
-- If both succeed:
COMMIT;
-- If error occurs:
ROLLBACK;
SAVEPOINT sp1;   -- Partial rollback point
```

**Conclusion:** Mastering these four categories enables a developer to perform every conceivable operation on a relational database — from schema design to user access control.

